</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">[http://www.gwen-morse.com/wiki/index.php/Linux Back to Linux]

= DDO on Gentoo Linux =

One game I particularly enjoy playing is Dungeons and Dragons Online. I focus my attention on the Sarlona and Orien servers.

I've been working on some [[Tips for DDO Noobs]].

== Installing DDO ==

No matter which version of wine you use to run DDO, you'll want a stable launcher. The native windows DDO launcher may or may not work depending on the code base and phase of the moon. The python launcher: [https://github.com/Lynx3d/pylotro pyloro launcher] should always work.

In Crossover Linux use the existing Crosstie.

I've switched my DDO install from Crossover to basic Wine. This allows me to eliminate any issues that may be caused by Crossover fixes that don't properly work.

[http://appdb.winehq.org/objectManager.php?sClass=application&amp;iId=2910 Official WineHQ Page for DDO]

For vanilla Wine on Gentoo distributions:

Make sure to get all the 32 bit wine packages, gnutls, and store Winetricks somewhere useful:
&lt;pre>
emerge wine
emerge -DuN gnutls
wget http://winetricks.org/winetricks
&lt;/pre>

gnults is needed to make the store browser function correctly.

Make sure your wine bottle is 32-bit (needed if you're on a 64-bit system). It's very important to delete any existing .wine directory before running winearch.
&lt;pre>
rm -rf .wine
WINEARCH=win32 WINEPREFIX=~/.wine winecfg
&lt;/pre>

Then, pre-install the Windows packages needed for DDO to run. The tahoma font is to reduce issues with the awesonium wrapper. Physx is only needed for nVidia video cards:
&lt;pre>
bash ./winetricks vcrun20{03,05,08,10} d3dx9 corefonts tahoma physx
&lt;/pre>

Once you're sure the .wine directory is set up and waiting, you can install DDO:
&lt;pre>
wine dndsetup.exe
&lt;/pre>

And build PyLOTRO from source...

To set the correct video memory size
&lt;pre>
winetricks videomemorysize=1024 (stealth)
 or
winetricks videomemorysize=512 (cowspot)
&lt;/pre>

If sound is crackling badly and you haven't disabled Pulseaudio, use this in your ~/.bashrc:
&lt;pre>
alias wine='PULSE_LATENCY_MSEC=60 wine' (wine)
 or
PULSE_LATENCY_MSEC=60 (crossover)
&lt;/pre>

== Specific Fixes ==

Crash Problem: crashing with an error indicating direct X 9.0c isn't installed - OpenGL issues - reinstall nVidia driver

No sound: use winecfg to update the libaries to include openal32.dll, Windows native version.

Exceptionally Bad Persistant Static: If you have functional sound without using the Windows native openal32, try removing it to clear up any static.

alt-tab crashes client: in the bottle un-set "Allow the window manager to control the windows" and set "emulate a virtual desktop". 

On cowspot, my desktop resolution is 1920x1200.

On stealth, my desktop resolution is 1920x1080.

Secondary Sound issue: Using either Crossover or vanilla Wine, DDO cannot share sound with another application (like Mangler, the Ventrilo client). This means I either get audio chat streams in DDO or I get audio chat in Mangler program). The stated fix for this is to change to the wine ALSA drivers. Directions on how to do this in Vanilla Wine found here: [http://askubuntu.com/questions/77210/how-to-change-the-default-audio-in-wine-to-alsa-only Change Default Audio To Alsa in Winetricks ]

Other crashing (Awesonium and other issues) discussed here: [http://appdb.winehq.org/objectManager.php?sClass=version&amp;iId=28606 WineHQ Database entry for DDO Update 18.3 ]

If the client gives messages about needing to install Visual C runtime, or just hangs badly on the launcher, you may want to manually install the Visual C redistributable packages from the Microsoft web site. I installed x86 2005, x86 2010, and the two service pack 1 versions.

If the store doesn't work, confirm 32-bit gnutls is installed.
